ğŸ§© Mongoose kya hota hai?

Mongoose ek ODM (Object Data Modeling) library hai MongoDB ke liye.

Yani simple shabdon me:

Ye ek bridge (pul) hai jo Express/Node.js aur MongoDB database ke beech connection banata hai.

ğŸ§  Tera samajhna:

â€œModel ek table/object ho gaya, aur schema uske andar ke values (columns/fields) ho gaye.â€

âœ… Bilkul theek!
Bas difference ye hai ki MongoDB NoSQL hai â€”
to yahan â€œtableâ€ aur â€œrowâ€ nahi kehte, balki â€œcollectionâ€ aur â€œdocumentâ€ bolte hain.

ğŸ§© Chalo compare karte hain (SQL vs MongoDB):
SQL Database	MongoDB (Mongoose)
Table	Collection
Row	Document
Column	Field
Schema	Schema (structure define karta hai)
Model	Collection ka interface (code me use hota hai)
ğŸ”¹ Example samjho:
ğŸ”¸ Mongoose me Schema:
const userSchema = new mongoose.Schema({
  name: String,
  email: String,
  age: Number
});


ğŸ‘‰ Yahaan:

name, email, age â†’ ye fields (columns) hain

Ye define karte hain ki document ke andar ka data kaisa hoga

ğŸ”¸ Model:
const User = mongoose.model('User', userSchema);


ğŸ‘‰ Yahaan:

User ek Model hai

Ye MongoDB me ek â€œusersâ€ collection banata hai

Aur uske andar document store karta hai

ğŸ”¸ Document (Data):
const newUser = new User({
  name: "Ritik Kumar",
  email: "ritik@gmail.com",
  age: 22
});

newUser.save();


ğŸ‘‰ Yahaan:

newUser ek document hai (SQL me â€œrowâ€ jaise)

Ye document users collection (table) ke andar store hoga

Iska structure schema ke hisaab se follow karega

ğŸ§  Simple real-world example:

Soch lo ek â€œUsersâ€ collection hai (table jaise):

name	email	age
Ritik Kumar	ritik@gmail.com
	22
Aman Singh	aman@gmail.com
	25
Ab yahaan:

Collection (Users) = Model

Row (ek user ka record) = Document

Column (name, email, age) = Schema ke fields

ğŸ’¬ Ek line me samjho:

ğŸ”¹ Schema = data ka design / blueprint (structure define karta hai)
ğŸ”¹ Model = us design se banta hua collection (code se interact karne ka tarika)
ğŸ”¹ Document = actual data (jo MongoDB me save hota hai)